Description: The Aarhus School Survey questionnaire (Aarhus; Rasmussen, et al., 2015) is a six item questionnaire intended to measure the respondents' own perceptions of computer gaming and Internet use. The questionnaire was developed by Rasmussen and colleagues for the Aarhus School Survey, Denmark in 2009. The participants rate how much they agree or disagree with six statements regarding computer gaming and internet use on a six-point Likert Rating scale from '1 = Strongly agree' to '5 = Strongly disagree'. The psychometric properties of the Aarhus questionnaires are limited (as of May 2022), but a study by Holstein and colleagues (2014) found Cronbach's alpha > 0.7 for both dimensions.

Instrument Title: Activities of Daily Living Scale - Instrumental
Description:
Activities of Daily Living (ADL) describes practical everyday tasks that have to be carried out at home in order to sustain a manageable and worthwhile life (Grov et.al, 2010).

The Instrumental Activities of Daily Living Scale (ADL-I) assesses function of complex activities of daily living, including housekeeping, responsibility for own medication, and food preparation.The assessment is done by a caregiver who is familiar with the patient. Six items may have a score from 1 to 5, producing a total score ranging from 6 to 30. A higher score indicates lower functioning (Lawton and Brody, 1969)

Instrument Title: Activities of Daily Living Scale - Personal
Description:
Activities of Daily Living (ADL) describes practical everyday tasks that have to be carried out at home in order to sustain a manageable and worthwhile life (Grov et.al, 2010).

The Physical Self-Maintenance Scale (PSMS), here refered to as Personal Activities of Daily Living (ADL-P), assesses basic function in activities of daily living, including feeding, dressing, and bathing. The assessment is done by a caregiver who is familiar with the patient. Six items may have a score from 1 to 5, producing a total score ranging from 6 to 30. A higher score indicates lower functioning (Lawton and Brody, 1969).

Description:
In the ATC classification system, drugs are divided into 14 main groups according to the organ or system on which they act and their chemical, pharmacological and therapeutic properties. Drugs are classified according to their main therapeutic use, on the basic principle of only one ATC code for each route of administration.

The structure of the code is illustrated below e.g. for metformin:

A Alimentary tract and metabolism (1st level, anatomical main group)
A10 Drugs used in diabetes (2nd level, therapeutic subgroup)
A10B Blood glucose lowering drugs, excl. insulins (3rd level, pharmacological subgroup)
A10BA Biguanides (4th level, chemical subgroup)
A10BA02 Metformin (5th level, chemical substance)

Thus, in the ATC system all plain metformin preparations are given the code A10BA02.

A searchable version of the ATC index is available on http://www.whocc.no/atc_ddd_index

A10B Blood glucose lowering drugs excl. insulins (3rd level pharmacological subgroup)
A10BA Biguanides (4th level chemical subgroup)
A10BA02 Metformin (5th level chemical substance)

Thus in the ATC system all plain metformin preparations are given the code A10BA02.

Instrument Title: Anxiety Disorders Interview Schedule for Children
Description:
Interview; guide is found in DSM-IV (copyright) under Anxiety Disorders Interview Schedule for Children, section Social Phobia. See also PDF for Norwegian version (copyright).
The questionnaire is diveded into groups of four questions. The first two abbreviations linkes the variable to the social anixiety interview guide. The next abbreviation(s) represents the specific question text, and the number its position within the group of four questions.
The first (#1) question in each group investigates the whether the participant feels fear or not of the situation described in the question, the second (#2) describes the fear in a scale given confirming answer in #1, the third (#3) asks if participant ever has tried to avoide situation (given #2> or equal to value 4), and the last (#4) investigates the rating of the avoidance (given confirmation in #3.

Description: Interacoustics AD25 automatic audiometers with TDH-39 earphones and MX 41/AR cushions were linked to personal computer, and the audiometry data were automatically stored on the personal computer. An automatic procedure with fixed frequencies was followed. Manual audiometry was conducted with people unable to follow the instructions for the automatic procedure. The test of each ear included the standard frequencies 0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 3, 4, 6 and 8 kHz. The audiometry session lasted from approximately 10 min per subject. For the present purpose, three hearing scores were completed: a) low frequency hearing level (0-25 kHz and 0.5 kHz thresholds, averaged over frequencies and both ears), b) middle frequency hearing level (1 kHz and 2 kHz), and c) high frequency hearing level (3 kHz, 4 kHz, 6 kHz, and 8 kHz). For more detailed description of the methodology, please see Tambs et al. 2003 or Tambs et al. 2004.

Description:
The activity sensors were programmed to measure over seven consecutive days. Two activity sensors were used, one on the right thigh (about 10 cm above the kneecap when sitting) and one in the middle of the L3 in the lower back. It was attached by using FlexiFix tape. The participants were told to remove the sensors after seven days and return them to HUNT by mail. If the participants found it unpleasant to walk with the sensors for seven days (severe itching / red skin) they were told to remove the sensors and return them back.

The AX3 is a small and lightweight (23×32.5×7.6 mm, weight 11 g) triaxial accelerometer with a configurable sampling frequency between 12.5 and 3,200 Hz and range between ±2 and ±16 g. The accelerometers were configured to record at 50 Hz and a range of ±8 g. The raw data was stored on a 512 MB internal memory and downloaded as binaryfile (Continuous Wave Accelerometer format) for visualization and further analysis. The AX3 OmGui software (version 1.0.0.37; Open Movement, Newcastle University, United Kingdom) was used to configure the sensors and download the accelerometer data (Bach et.al 2021)

Description: Self-reported scale developed to measure the severity of fatigue. The questionnaire has 11 items, and was developed to assess severity of fatigue symptoms. The seven first items measures physical fatigue and the four last items measure mental fatigue. The items are rated on a 4-point Likert scale (e.g. 0=better than usual, 3=much worse than usual). Two scoring systems exist, the first by summing up the likert scores, and the other by using bimodal scores (0,1,2,3 and 0,0,1,1 respectively). Fatigue “caseness” has been defined by Chalder et al., 1993, to be between 3 and 4 (4=<), with symptoms of fatigue lasting longer than six months.

Instrument Title: Chronic Kidney Disease Epidemiology collaboration equations
Description:
Equation for estimated glomerular filtration (eGFR) is from the Chronic Kidney Disease Epidemiology collaboration (CKD-EPI):

eGFR = 141 x min[serum creatinine/k ,1]^a x max[serum creatinine/k ,1]^1.209 x 0.996^age x 1.018 [if female] x 1.159 [if Black]

k= 0.7 for females and 0.9 for males
a= -0.329 for females and -0.411 for males
min indicates the minimum of kreatinin/k or 1 and max indicated the maximun of kreatinin/k or 1.

SI Units:
eGFR = ml/min/1.73 m2
serum creatinine =mg/dl
age = years

This formula is valid only for adults over 18 years of age. The CKD-EPI was derived and validated by Levey e al. The CKD-EPI equation performs better than MDRD (Modification of Diet in Reanl Disease Study) equetion if higher GFR.

Reference: Levey e al. A new equation to estimate glomerular filtration rate. Ann Intern Med. 2009;150:604-612.

Description: The CDR is a 5-item scale used to characterize six domains of cognitive and functional performance applicable to Alzheimer disease and related dementias. The six domains are Memory, Orientation, Judgment & Problem Solving, Community Affairs, Home & Hobbies, and Personal Care. The scoring is based on all available information about the patient. An overall CDR score is calculated through the use of an algorithm giving precedence to Memory. A score of 0 indicates no dementia, a score of 0,5 indicates possible dementia, whereas the scores 1, 2 and 3 indicate mild, moderate and severe dementia, respectively. (Hughes et al., 1982)

Description: Manufacturer: Roche Diagnostics, USA

The CONOR Mental Health Index (CONOR-MHI) is a seven item, 4 point Liker rating scale, intended as a measure of mental distress for epidemiological studies. The CONOR-MHI is a partly modified questionnaire based on the General Health Questionnaire (GHQ; Goldberg, 1972), the Hopkins Symptom Check List (HSCL-10; Derogatis, et al., 1974), as well as other health surveys. According to the validation study by Søgaard and colleagues (2003), the internal consistency of the CONOR-MHI was high (Crohnbach's alpha > 0.8), and was strongly correlated with the HADS (Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale) and HSCL-10. In calculating the mean score on the CONOR-MHI, the two items relating to calmness and optimimism are reverse-coded. For dicothomization a cut off of >= 2.15 is used (Søgaard et al., 2003).

Description:
CSQ assesses the frequency in the use of different strategies for coping with pain.

It was developed by Rosenstiel and Keefe (1983), and originaly contains 42 items scored on a 7-point Likert scale (0=Never do, 6= Always do that). A one-item version of the CSQ has been developed by Jensen et al (2003), that assess the seven subscales that reflect the dimensions measured in the CSQ, which is diverting attention, reinterpreting pain sensations, catastrophizing, ignoring sensations, coping self-statements, praying/hoping and increasing activity level. The questionnaire has been translated and validated in Norwegian cancer patients.
Permission to use the CSQ was given by dr. Keefe to Tormod Landmark for the HUNT pain study. Copyright: Dr. A.K. Rosenstiel. The questions are selected from the two-item version of CSQ.

The version used in HUNT 3 has been published in NFER-Nelson ”Health Psychology Portfolio” and in Pain 104 (2003).

Instrument Title: Cortex MetaMac II; mixing chamber gas-analyzer ergospirometry
Description:
Manufacturer: Cortex, Leipzig, Germany

Used for testing of submaximal and maximal oxygen uptake.

Before starting the testing procedure several Metamax II apparatus were tested against Douglas-bag and iron lung (Cortex, Leipzig, Germany). Two Metamax II apparatus were sent back to Cortex because of unstable recordings (both ventilation and carbon monoxide analysis) and replaced by two new apparatus that were tested and as described above. Therefore, all Metamax apparatus used in the HUNT Fitness project were both valid and reliable.

Test-retest correlation of oxygen-uptake for the test-personnel in the HUNT Fitness project was 0.99, p<0.001 and coefficient of variation was 1.8%. Bland-Altman plot were constructed where differences in two tests of maximal oxygen uptake (and sub maximal) from each person (test-1 minus test 2) were plotted against the average of the two tests ((test-1 + test-2 )/2). Average difference was -0.04 ml/kg/min and standard deviation of the difference was 1.0. One can therefore expect that 95% of all observations are at the average ((test-1 + test-2 )/2) ± 2 standard deviations. Therefore, we can expect values to vary between -0.04 -2·1 to -0.04 + 2·1 if we test maximal oxygen uptake twice in the same person (within a short time period). We therefore have an accuracy that is within the limitations of the accuracy of Metamax II according to the producers (Cortex, Leipzig, Germany) specifications.

The test personnel that performed the tests of maximal oxygen uptake had performed on average 1587 tests of maximal oxygen uptake each before starting up the HUNT Fitness project. Number of test performed before start-up varied between 100 and 5 500 tests and care was taken to follow-up the test procedures with the less experienced test personnel the first 2 months of data collection.

Description:
Performed by one experienced dentist and one experienced dental hygienist. No radiographs were used because radiographs for epidemiological studies are seldom ethical, they expose people to radiation with no personal benefit.

Tooth numbering system of the Fédération Dentaire Internationale (FDI) is used, also known as ISO 3950.

Tooth surfaces explanation ("CuStat.."):
- m = mesial
- d = distal
- l = lingual
- b = buccal
- o = occlusal
- p = pit

- All teeth examined were permanent teeth.
- Variables "Diast..": if tooth was missing, the size of the diastema was registred as well as any replacing constructions.
- Tooth surfaces ("CuStat...") and diastemas ("Diast..") of the wisdom teeth were not examined.
- Dentures & prosthetics (variablenames: "Prost.."): when there was more than one answer applicable, only the highest score was registred.

Description:
Measurements based on automatic oscillometric method.

HUNT4: All teams used Dinamap CARESCAPE V100 (GE Healthcare) with GE TruSignal for pulse oximetry.

HUNT2 and HUNT3:
Measurements at the stationary team in the five larger municipalities:
HUNT3 Dinamap Critikon model 8100
HUNT2 Dinamap Critikon model 845XT

Measurements at the mobile team in the 19 smaller municipalities: Dinamap XL model 9301 from Johnson & Johnson Medical Inc. Measures mean arterial pressure (MAP) directly, i.e. does not compute/estimate it from systolic and diastolic pressure.

Blood pressure was measured in a sitting position according to standardized methods (Holmen 2003). Three consecutive automatic oscillometric BP-measurements were recorded at 1-min intervals and the mean of the second and the third readings were calculated. Blood pressure was registered to the nearest 2 mm Hg.

Cuff size was adjusted after measuring the arm circumference. The measurements were started after the participant had been seated for two minutes with the cuff on the arm, and the arm resting on a table. Blood pressures reported in most papers are the mean of the second and third systolic and diastolic blood pressures. Blood pressures measured with the Dinamap device are slightly lower than those measured with a sphygmomanometer, especially for diastolic blood pressure (Lund-Larsen 1997).

Description:
Osteometer MediTech, Inc, Hawthorne, CA 90250.
DTX200 is very similar to the DTX100. DTX200 estimates the bone mineral content (BMC, grams) and bone mineral density (BMD, grams/cm2) in the distal section of the forearm (radius and ulna). The ultradistal site is not measured.
DTX200 uses the technicque of X-ray absorptiometry. The X-ray tube is supplied with a high voltage of 55 kV, The beam is filtered with tin (Sn), yielding two effective energy levels for separation of bone and soft tissue (fat, muscle).
Due to two energy levels it was not nessary to fill the container with water as it was for DTX100.
Quality controlled had to be perfomed every day before the first patient scan. DTX200 automatically corrects for different amounts of fat mass in the forearm.

Precision and accuracy (according to manufactuar):
In vivo precision in measurement of 15 volunteers 5 times each with repositioning between all replicate measurements;
Distal BMC 0.68%, distal BMD 0.87, nROI BMD 1.11%

Accuracy measured with repeated readning using a phantom is within plus/minus 0.5%
The instrument was mainly used at team I in HUNT 3.

Description: Eating problems were measured using a 7-item version of the Eating Attitude Test (EAT-7). The original instrument developed by Garner and Garfinkel (1979) contained 40 items, which was later shortened to 26 items by Garner, Olmsted, Bohr, and Garfinkel (1982). EAT-12 was constructed based on a study of the psychometric features of EAT-26, containing three factors: dieting, bulimia and food preoccupation and oral control. In Young-HUNT, EAT-12 was reduced to EAT-7, including the two factors of oral control (EAT-A) and bulimia and food preoccupation (EAT-B). Oral control included 4 questions (max score 8), while bulimia and food preoccupation included 3 questions (max score 6) from EAT-12. The 7-item-version has been validated towards the 12-item version (Bjørnelv, Mykletun, & Dahl, 2002).

Description:
The version used in HUNT is similar to part of the Eysenck Personality Questionnaire (EPQ). EPQ includes three personality traits: Neuroticism (N), Extraversion (E) and Psychoticism (P). The three psychometric scales are originally based upon 101 item EPQ, and later datasets usually consists of 90 item EPQ (Barrett 1985).
Items from the Eysenck Personality Questionnaire, six for each of the dimensions E, N, and P, were chosen for a short-form version. The selection of combinations of items that best predicted the scores from the original items was based on analyses of a full-scale data material (Eysenck & Tambs (1990)). These analyses are described elsewhere in Norwegian publications (Tambs in Sandanger et.al (red.)(2004)).
The analyses showed correlations between scores from the original instrument and the short-form instrument at .90 for E, .90 for N, and .78 (.82 if weighing the items before summing) for P. Alpha reliabilities were .67, .65, and .39, respectively. A version slightly modified to better suit the youngest YH participants with all three dimensions is included in YH1+2. A version including only E and N is part of the H3.

Copyright issues are not addressed. The items to the short-version were taken from the original version (Eysenck & Eysenck (1975)). A modified version, EPQ-R, was published in 1985 (Eysenck et.al. (1985)). It is not clear whether the original EPQ is still copyright-protected (ref Kristian Tambs).

Description:
Manufacturer: BD Biosciences, Alphen aan den Rijn, Netherlands

Method: Performed in non-fasting serum samples. Analysed by BD(TM) Cytometric Bead Array (CBA) Human Inflammatory Cytokine Kit (BD Biosciences, Alphen aan den Rijn, Netherlands). To lower the detection limit of the kit, there were used procedures that differed slightly from the recommendations of the manufacturer. In brief, 10µl of thawed serum was mixed with 10 µl of diluted capture bead suspension in a sample tube. Subsequently 10µl of PE-labelled detection reagent were added followed by 3 h of incubation in darkness. Wash buffer (200 µl) was added and the samples were centrifuged at 200xg. The supernatant was aspirated and the bead pellet resuspended in wash buffer (150µl). The finished bead suspension were analysis on a FACSCalibur flow cytometer. (BD Biosciences, Alphen aan den Rijn, Netherlands ).


Detection limit: 2.5 pg/ml

Range: 1.0-5000 pg/ml

Intra assay precision (%CV): 9% in the low range (80pg/ml), 6% in the middle range (625pg/ml) and 10% in the high range (2,500pg/ml)

Inter assay precision (%CV): 8% in the low range (80pg/ml), 15% in the middle range (625pg/ml) and 13% in the high range (2,500pg/ml)

For information: The cytokine concentrations were often near the concentration of the lowest calibrator, and depending on the analyte, the levels of cytokine in part of the samples remained undetectable (set as value=0 ). In some samples, outlier levels far above the standard curves (>5000 pg/ml) were seen. Consentrations >10000 was set as 10000.

Description:
Cited from Nilsson M et al. 2003, page 67: Heartburn and acid regurgitation are symptoms of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GORD), and the use of questionnaires to assess these symptoms is validated as a reliable measurement of the true occurrence of reflux (Klauser AG et al. 1990, Locke GR et al. 1994, Ter RB et al. 1997 Revicki DA et al. 1998).

Cited from Ness-Jensen E et al. 2012 page 1391: GORS is assessed in HUNT2 and HUNT3 surveys where participants were asked to what degree they have had heartburn or acid regurgitation during the previous 12 months. In HUNT 2, the GORS question was part of the initial questionnaire (Q1). In HUNT 3 the GORS question was part of the second questionnaire (Q2) and as part of the Non-Participants questionnaire (QNP). The frequency of GORS was not directly assessed in HUNT 2 Q1 and HUNT 3 Q2, in this matter the participants were asked to report both their degree and frequency of GORS in a validation study after HUNT 2 (GLUP) and in the HUNT3 Non-Participants-study. To assess the frequency of GORS the participants were asked how often they had heartburn or acid regurgitation complaints.

Description:
Manufacturer: HemoCue AB, Ängelholm, Sweden.
Consist of a small analyzer and disposable microcuvettes.

Capillary whole blood glucose analysis done by well-trained health personnel the same day the participant attended.
The HemoCue analyser convertes the capillary whole blood values to capillary serum values.

Method: The red blood cells are broken apart by saponin to measure the glucose content in the red blood cells and plasma. A glucose dehydrogenase - NAD enzyme combination is used to form NADH from available glucose and the MTT chromogene is formed to colored formazin. The colored formazin is quantified photometrically with a two-wavelenght method (667 and 840 nm)

In HUNT2 by means of HemoCue Glucose Beta-glucose system.
In HUNT3 by means of HemoCue Glucose 201+ system.

Description:
Manufacturer: Hewlett-Packard Inc. Agilent Technologies Inc.

Plasma lipids were extracted with butanol and phospholipids isolated by column chrormotography after adding diheptadecanoyl-glycerophosphocholin and butylated hydroxytoulene (Sigma Chemical) as an internal standard and antioxidant, respectively. The phospholipids were transmethylated and quantified by GLC on a Hewlett-Packard 5890A using a 30m SP2330 fused silica capillary column (inner diameter 0.25mm and film thickness 0.20µm; Supelco Inc.). A method developed by Professor Dr.med Kristian Bjerve.

The results is expressed as mg phospholipid FA per Litre plasma and recalculated to a percentage by weight (wt%) on the basis of twenty-two identified FA.

The betweenseries CV were 3.7%, 3.7% and 4.9%, respectively, for 20:4n-6, 20:5n-3 and 22:6n-3 when measured as mg/l. The corresponding CV were reduced
to 2.2%, 2.4% and 3.5%, respectively when concentrations were expressed as wt%.

Description:
The HADS is a 14 item scale developed in 1983 by Snaith RP and Zigmond AS. Copyright http://www.mapi-research.fr/t_03_serv_dist_Cduse_HADS.htm.
Copyright owner Snaith and Zigmond, Licence GL Assessment, whilst Mapi Research Trust is responsible for licenced translations.

In 1989, professor Ulrik F. Malt developed and validated a Norwegian translation through collaboration with professor Snaith. This version has been extensively used at Oslo University Hospital.
In the planning of HUNT 2 the psychiatric research group (professor Alv Dahl and coworkers) were not aware of this translation and developed their own Norwegian version of the HADS.
In HUNT 2 the questions on mental distress, CONOR MHI included a question close to one of the HADS items; In the last two weeks, have you felt nervous and restless. Due to limited space in the questionnaire, the corresponding question in HADS “During the last week: I feel tense or wound up” was omitted. The CONOR MHI derived question is included in the final scores according to standard procedure. Further, there was a minor difference in the Norwegian wording in the questioni“I feel restless as if I have to be on the move” between the two translations (må være i aktivitet versus må være aktiv).

In HUNT 3 the translated version used in HUNT 2 was included, and this time all 14 items were included in the instrument according to the original version by Snaith and Zigmond.

The Norwegian version of the HADS included in HUNT 2 and HUNT 3 has good psychometric properties and is in close agreement to the original questionnaire developed by Snaith and Zigmond. (Mykletun A., Stordal E., Dahl A. A. (2001)).

The classification of scores on the HADS-D and HADS-A subscales commonly used are: 0-7 normal, 8-10 mild, 11-14 moderate and 15-21 severe symptoms.
Validation studies indicate high sensitivity and specificity of a score > 8 for both subscales (Bjelland, Dahl, Haug &Neckelmann 2002, Herrmann 1997)

Data from the HUNT2-survey was among other things utilized in order to examine psychometric properties for the HADS instrument (Mykletun et al. 2001), the relationship between HADS and various somatic health problems in the general population (Stordal et al. 2001), monthly variation in depression, anxiety and their comorbidity (Stordal et al. 2008), association between depression, anxiety and thyroid function (Engum et al. 2002) and myocardial infarction and risk for both anxiety and depression (Bjerkeset et al. 2005).

Description: Age is computed as the number of days between birth (as registered by the Norwegian National Registry) and the date in question, divided by 365.2425 (the average number of days per year in the Gregorian calendar), rounded to one decimal. Note that this means that people are considered (say) 40.0 years old as early as 18 days before their 40th birthday.

Description: DCQ HUNT is a short adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) measure with non-intrusive items that include subjective evaluations of childhood. Instrument Title: Inhouse made questions for the Baseline questionnaires in HUNT
Description:
This is an inhouse question made for the baseline questionnaires, Q1 and Q2 used in the HUNT surveys. For questions used in more than one survey, the question text may have been modified for improvement from the first survey to the next.

Some questions may also have been used in other health surveys in Norway, like:
- The Tromsø Study (managed by the University of Tromsø)
- Oslo Health Study (HUBRO, 2000-2001, managed by Norwegian Institute of Public Health)
- The Cardiovascular diesase prevention program (first started in 1972) organized by earlier National Mass Radiography Service (1943-1985), then the Norwegian Health investigation (1985-2001), and now the Norwegian Institute of Public Health. One of the two questionnaires was used in the cardiovascular disease study performed in three Norwegian counties, Finnmark, Sogn og Fjordane and Oppland (1974-1676) and the second questionnaire was used in the so-called "Age-40 programme" (started in 1983 in Oslo and was nation-wide in 1993).

Description:
This is an inhouse question made for the Complementary and alternative medicine (CAM) study in the HUNT3-4 survey by professor Aslak Steinsbekk (lead of the CAM projects in the HUNT3 and HUNT4).

The questions were made, in addition to the international literature, especially with reference to Scandinavian population studies that map the use of
alternative treatment (Norway: HUNT 2, SSB, HUBRO, HEDOPP, Tromsø, Finnmark, NOU 1998: 21; Denmark: Susy 2000; Sweden : Stockholmare och den komplementära medicinen 2000). Furthermore, the work was influenced by and based on parts of the work that resulted in the following two publications:
Baldwin CM, et al. (2004) Complementary and conventional medicine: a concept map, BMC Complement Altern Med. and Quandt SA, et al. (2009) Development of an international questionnaire to measure use of complementary and alternative medicine (I-CAM-Q). J Altern Complement Med.

For questions used in more than one survey, the question text may have been adjusted for improvement.

Description:
IPAQ comprises a set of 4 questionnaires, a long and a short version for use by either telephone or self-administered. The purpose of the questionnair is to provide common instruments that can be used to obtain internationally comparable data on health–related physical activity.

It was developed in 1998 and was followed by extensive reliability and validity testing undertaken across 12
countries (14 sites) during 2000. The final results suggest that these measures have acceptable measurement properties for use in many settings and in different languages, and are suitable for national population-based prevalence studies of participation in physical activity.

More detailed information on the IPAQ process and the research methods used in the development of IPAQ instruments is available at www.ipaq.ki.se and Booth, M.L. (2000).

The International Prostate Symptom Scale (IPSS) is an eight question (7 questions about symptoms and 1 question about quality of life) screening tool for bening prostatic hyperplasia (BPH). It was originally created by the American Urological Association (AUA-7) in 1992, however it lacked the 8th QOL question.

Ref: Barry MJ, Fowler FJ Jr, O'Leary MP, et. al. The American Urological Association symtom index for bening prostatic hyperplasia. The Measurement Committee of the American Urological Association. J Urol. 1992 Nov; 148 (5): 1549-57

The answer alternatives are slightly different HUNT, by using one of three instead of less than half and two of three instead of more than half.

Copyright: MAPI Research Trust. User is required to complete and sign a User Agreement' in which specific conditions requested by the author are detailed.
(Ref: Steinar Hunskår and Arnfinn Seim)

Instrument Title: Interpersonal violence, brief lifetime trauma screen
Description: The questions in Young-HUNT brief lifetime trauma screen regarding interpersonal violence was derived from the University of California at Los Angeles Post-traumatic Stress Disorder Reaction Index (UCLA PTSD Reaction Index) (Steinberg et al., 1998) and adapted to the Norwegian context (e.g. neighborhood shootings are not very frequent in Norway, and were therefore left out of the questionnaire). The original formulation of the questions regarding sexual abuse was not approved by REK since they were to direct and could lead to criminalization of persons. They were therefore rewritten to more unspecific questions to suit the demands of HUNT and REK.The UCLA PTSD Reaction Index was developed from the Survey of Children’s Exposure to Community Violence (Richters & Saltzman, 1990), and the Community Violence Exposure Survey (CVES) (Saltzman et al., 1998).

Description:
Manufacturer: Gebrüder Martin, W., Germany.

Squeeze dynanometer that measures grip strength in kilopascals or bar. The set included 3 sizes of rubber balls for use according to hand size.

Procedure:
Grip strength was measured in non-dominant arm. The arm should not be supported on table or thigh. The participants squeezed the Vigorimeter rubber balls with all their strenght three times to evaluate the grup strenght. The size of the rubber ball was adjusted according to their hand size, and 1 minute of rest was given in-between the attempts. The mean between the two highest results was registered.

Description:
This is a five-item version of the mental health inventory which was developed by the RAND Corporation in a health insurance experiment (Davies et al, 1988). The questions are also published as an independent screening test (Berwick et al, 1991) and they are included in the MOS 36-item Short Form Survey Instrument (SF-36).


According the HUNT Pain Study group, the RAND-36 can be used free of charge and without any written permission. The items are different from SF36v2 in that they are rated on a 6-point Likert scale, and have a different scoring procedure.

Description:
Blood pressure was measured in sitting position, after at least four minutes with the cuff placed on the right upper arm. The participant was not allowed to speak during the measurements or see the scale of the sphygmomanometer. The arm was rested on the table at the heart-level. The radial pulse was palpated. The cuff was rapidly inflated until the column of mercury rose 20-30 mm above the point where the radial pulse disappeared. A stethoscope was placed in the hollow of the elbow. The systolic pressure was read when the first pulse was heard with the stethoscope. The diastolic pressure was read when the pulse disappeared completely. When the pulse could be heard right down the zero mmHg, the diastolic pressure was given where the sound of the pulse became weaker and more round or "wolly". In this case an additional measurement was taken after one minute.

The cuff was inflated twice with an interval of at least one minute. The air was completely expelled from the cuff after each reading. Both the systolic and diastolic pressure were read off to the nearest 2 mmHg

The participant was not allowed to speak during the measurements or see the scale of the sphygmomanometer. The arm was rested on the table at the heart-level. The radial pulse was palpated. The cuff was rapidly inflated until the column of mercury rose 20-30 mm above the point where the radial pulse disappeared. A stethoscope was placed in the hollow of the elbow. The systolic pressure was read when the first pulse was heard with the stethoscope. The diastolic pressure was read when the pulse disappeared completely. When the pulse could be heard right down the zero mmHg the diastolic pressure was given where the sound of the pulse became weaker and more round or "wolly". In this case an additional measurement was taken after one minute.

The cuff was inflated twice with an interval of at least one minute. The air was completely expelled from the cuff after each reading. Both the systolic and diastolic pressure were read off to the nearest 2 mmHg

Description: The Meta-Memory Questionnaire (MMQ) is a nine-item self-report questionnaire designed to assess subjective memory performance (Bosnes, et al., 2020), The scale was developed for the NORA-study (Fromholdt & Berg, 1997). Participants are asked to respond on a three-point Likert rating scale how well nine statements fit their own experiences in relation to memory. A total score ranging from 9 to 27 can be calculated, with higher scores indicate more severe memory impairment. Almkvist and colleagues (2017) identified two distinct components of the MMQ, Component 1 'long-term memory' (5 items) and Component 2 'short-term memory' (4 items), while Bosnes (et al., 2020) reported Component 2 significantly assocated to objective episodic, semantic and work/short-term memory.

Instrument Title: Modification of diet in renal disease study
Description:
Equation for estimated glomerular filtration (eGFR) is from the Modification of diet in renal disease study (MDRD):

eGFR = 175 x [serum creatinine/88.4]^-1.154 x [age]^-0.203 x 0.742 [if female] x 1.212 [if Black]

SI Units:
eGFR = ml/min/1.73 m2
serum creatinine = µmol/L
age = years

The equation has been validated in Caucasian and African American populations between the age of 18-70 with impared kidney function (eGFR<60 mL/min/1.73m2) (Levey AS et al, 2009)

This formula is valid only for adults over 18 years of age. It is adviced to use the CKD-epi (Chronic Kidney Disease Epidemiology collaboration) equations if the persons are over 70 years of age and if eGFR>60 mL/min/1.73m2.

Instrument Title: Modified Medical Research Council (mMRC) dyspnea scale
Description:
The mMRC is a symptom questionnaire with five statements on various physical activities graded 0-4. It measures perceived respiratory disability and is used to grade the effect of dyspnea on daily activites. It is validated for assessment of the degree of breathlessness (dyspnea) (Hajiro et.al 1998). The mMRC is a modification of the original MRC dyspnea scale (last revised in 1986) (Mahler et.al 1988).

Internationally the most commonly used modified British Medical Research Council Dyspnea Scale (mMRC) includes five items with increasing dyspnea as a scale where the participant shall tick off the alternative that best describes her/his dyspnea. This version is used in HUNT4 and in Tromsø7.

In HUNT2-4 all items were included but asked as five separate questions to be answered “No” or “Yes”. This was done in order to increase compatibility with the Hordaland Study. Based on these answers an mMRC was constructed choosing the affirmative answer to the highest dyspnea level of the five questions as level of the scale. Inconsistencies in reported level of symptoms were also cross-checked with other questions on limitations of respiratory disease/symptoms in the interview.

In HUNT2 and HUNT4 the questions were assessed using a questionnaire, and in HUNT3 as an interview.

Description: Originally, the NPI assessed ten types of neuropsychiatric symptoms occurring in dementia patients. Later, two neurovegetative items were added to the scale. Hence, the present version has 12 items. The assessment takes place in an interview with the caregiver who knows the patient best. The frequency (1-4), the intensity (1-3) and the caregiver stress (0-5) are assessed for each item. Frequency and intensity are multiplied for each item. The sum of all items gives a total score ranging from 0 to 144. A higher score indicates more severe symptoms. (Cummings et al., 1994;Cummings, 1997)

Description:
The NEUROPSYCHIATRIC INVENTORY – NURSING HOME VERSION (NPI-NH) was developed to help
characterize the neuropsychiatric symptoms and psychopathology of patients with Alzheimer’s disease and other dementias when the patients are residents in extended care facilities or other care settings where information is gathered from professional caregivers.

The NPI-NH was derived from the Neuropsychiatric Inventory (NPI), which was originally developed for the assessment of neuropsychiatric symptoms and psychopathology in community-dwelling patients where information was obtained from family caregivers. The content of the questions of the NPI and NPI-NH are identical but have been rephrased appropriately. In addition, the caregiver distress scale of the NPI has been changed to an occupational disruptiveness scale for the NPI-NH to allow an assessment of the impact of behavioral disturbances on professional caregivers.

Description:
Transient evoked OAEs (TEOAEs) and distortion product OAEs (DPOAEs) were recorded both ears in sound proof booths (C-A Tegner AB) or in relatively quiet but not soundproof rooms with two parallel systems operated by one audio technician and one trained assistant. Not all subjects were tested for each ear and with both OAE techniques because the audiometric test had a higher maximal capacity and the highest priority. A standard ILO92 DPOAE B-type probe was positioned in the subject`s ear canal by a foam E-A-R-type eartip. The left ear was always tested first. A detailed description of the technical procedure is given in Engdahl, 2002.
TEOAEs were evoked by 80 μs rectangular pulses with a presentation rate of 50/s using the default stimulus voltage with no adjustment of gain, presented with the non-linear differential method. An artefact rejection noise limit was set at 4 mPa (peak 46 dB SPL). Online, the signal was windowed from 2.5 to 20 ms post stimulus and band pass filtered from 600 to 6000 Hz. Offline, the signal was octave filtered with center frequencies of 1, 2, and 4 kHz. The following variables were analyzed: the estimated TEOAE level defined as the root mean square (rms) of the average of the two sub averages, the cross correlation coefficient (CCC) between the two sub averages and the estimated noise level defined as the rms of the difference between the two sub averages.
The DPAOE test consisted of presenting two primary tones at frequencies f₁ and f₂ and levels L₁ and L₂. The frequency ratio f₂/f₁ was fixed at 1.22. The stimulus levels were held constant at L₁=65 dB SPL and L₂=55 dB SPL. The amplitude of the DPOAEs occurring at the 2f₁-f₂ frequency was measured with f₂ frequencies at 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, and 8 kHz. The noise level estimated from the ten Fourier components nearest to but not including the 2f₁-f₂ frequency and its standard deviation.

Not all subjects were tested for each ear and with both OAE techniques because the audiometric test had a higher maximal capacity and the highest priority. A standard ILO92 DPOAE B-type probe was positioned in the subject`s ear canal by a foam E-A-R-type eartip. The left ear was always tested first. The following variables were analyzed: the estimated TEOAE level defined as the root mean square (rms) of the average of the two sub averages the cross correlation coefficient (CCC) between the two sub averages and the estimated noise level defined as the rms of the difference between the two sub averages.

Description: The leisure time physical activity (LTPA) and occupational activity items used in the HUNT2 survey is validated in Kurtze et al. (2007). The item regarding “light” physical activity included in the LTPA did not meet the desired requirements as to reproducibility and correlation with the other measures concerning physical activity.

Description:
Questions on specific posttraumatic stress reactions were selected in collaboration with the authors of the 20-item child version of the UCLA PTSD index for DSM-IV.174 (In the original version responses are rated across a 5-point Likert scale.) The questions on posttraumatic stress reactions were introduced as follows: 'If you have experienced any such event (referring to exposure to interpersonal violence), do you still think a lot about what happened?' Yes-responders were further asked: i) 'Do you have frightening thoughts, hear sounds or picture what happened, even if you don't want to?' (corresponding to the UCLA3B1-item); ii) 'When something reminds you of what happened, do you get very upset, afraid or sad?' (corresponding to the UCLA2B4-item); and iii) 'Do you attempt not to talk about it, think about it or have feelings around what happened?' (Corresponding to the UCLA9C1-item).
In an unpublished analysis of a population of Norwegian children (n=122) who were exposed to the 2004 tsunami,99 the selected items had the highest correlation amongst items within their category (intrusion vs avoidance), with item- to full-scale correlation ranging from 0.46 for UCLA3B1 to 0.61 for UCLA9C1 and 0.67 for UCLA2B4.

Instrument Title: Problem Areas In Diabetes Scale 5 item questionnaire
Description:
A 5 item short-form of PAID used for measure of diabetes related emotinal distress in adults with diabetes.

PAID was originally developed for clinical use by W.H. Polonsku and colleagues at the Joslin Diabetes Center in Boston, USA (1995). PAID has been translated into many languages and was translated into Norwegian by Bergen Univeristy College in 2009.

The 5-item short-form has been validated by McGuire B. et al. Short-form measures of diabetes-related emotional distress: The Problem Areas in Diabetes Scale (PAID)-5 and PAID-1, Diabetologia 2010.

The answers are ranked in a scale from 0 (no problem) to 4 (serious problem). Scores from each statements are summed up and can range from 0-20 with higher scores suggesting greater diabetes-realted emotinal distress.

Description:
Psoriasis is characterized as mild, moderate or severe according to the amount of the body surface area (BSA) affected and the severity of redness, thickness and scaling of the skin.

Using the surface of the hand to equal 1% BSA psoriasis is considered; MILD if less than 3% of the body is affected, MODERATE if 3-10% is affected and SEVERE if more than 10% is affected.

Description:
In Yung HUNT3 an eight items scale were selected based on extensive statistical procedures from the Resilience Scale for Adolescents (READ) that originally contains 28 items. The READ is based on the previously developed Resilience Scale for Adults (RSA;33 items). The selected READitems belong to the following two factors:
Social competence (4 items)
Family cohesion (4 items)
Factors not included in HUNT were Personal competence, Structured style and Social resources.

Description: The Resilience Scale for Adults (RSA) was developed by Hjemdal and colleagues (2001) to measure protective resoures promoting adult resilience. The RSA is a 45 item questionnaire, comprising five dimensions of protective resources. In a validation study conducted by Friborg, Hjemdal, Rosenvinge, and Martinussen (2003), Cronbach's alpha ranged from .67 to .90, four-month test-retest correlations ranged from .69 to .84, while the convergent and discriminant validity were supported in relation to the SCO (Sense of Coherence Scale; Antonovsky, 1993) and HSCL (Hopkins Symptom Checklist; Nettelbladt et al., 1993), respectively.

Description:
Revised Oral Assessment Guide (ROAG) is a standardized instrument to be used by non-dental professionals to observe, assess and document oral health problems in elderly (1). The Oral Assessment Guide (OAG) was originally developed by Eilers et al. (3) and was later revised by Andersson et al. to be used among elderly patients (ROAG and ROAG-Jönköping) (1-2, 4). ROAG-J is used in HUNT 4 70+ with permission from Pia Andersson and Senior-Alert and were based on the version from 2015.

ROAG-J include nine categories to assess oral health: voice, swallowing, lips, mucous membranes, tongue, saliva, gums, teeth and dentures. These categories are graded from 0-3 where 0 = not relevant to assess; 1 = normal condition; 2 = moderate changes/deviations; 3= severe changes/deviations. Scores of 2 or 3 in one or more categories are considered as an oral health problem. ROAG-J also contains additional observations regarding teeth/no teeth and dentures/no dentures in lower/upper jaw.

The Swedish version of ROAG-J is translated to Norwegian by Center for Oral Health, services and Research (TkMidt) to be used in HUNT4 70+ survey. The category about dentures are split into two, where the visual assessment (“look”) of the dentures is assessed and reported by the health care workers, whereas the function of the dentures is self-reported by the elderly participants. To perform the “saliva-test” in ROAG-J in HUNT4 70+ the lower end of a plastic toothbrush is used. Additional information regarding saliva under the tongue, loose teeth and root remnant are included in the oral health observation in HUNT4 70+.

The oral health assessment in HUNT4 70+ are performed by non-dental healthcare workers from the different municipality or by nursing student from NORD University or NTNU after training from a dentist or dental hygienist from TkMidt.

Instrument Title: Short Form 8 Health-Related Quality of Llife
Description:
The SF-8 health survey is a health related quality of life questionnaire. It is a shortened version of SF-36, and includes one question for each of the eight dimensions in the SF-36. The eight dimensions are: physical functioning, social functioning, role limitations due to physical problems, role limitations due to emotional problems, mental health, energy/vitality, pain and general health perception. The dimensions can also be combined into standardized summary scores, one physical component summary (PCS8) and one mental health component summary (MCS8). Specification for calculation of the summary scores is provided from QualityMetric SF health survey.

SF-8 is a registered trademark, copyright: QualityMetric Inc.. It is not allowed to modify, change or translate the SF-8 health survey or the scoring algorithms. Licensed agreement is agreed between NTNU (Norwegian University of Science and Technology) and QualityMetric Inc. for the use of the instrument in non-commercial research in the project HUNT Chronic Pain survey.

Description: Performance based test of lower extremity function. Consists of 3 components: 4m gaitspeed in preferred speed, sit-to-stand x 5 and the ability to keep static balance for 10 seconds in three standing positions: feet together, semitandem and tandem. Each component is timed and provides a score 0-4 based on the timing, resulting in a total score 0-12, higher score indicating better performance. Source: 1.Guralnik, J. M., Ferrucci, L., Pieper, C. F., Leveille, S. G., Markides, K. S., Ostir, G. V., et al. (2000). Lower extremity function and subsequent disability: Consistency across studies, predictive models, and value of gait speed alone compared with the short physical performance battery. Journal of Gerontology: Medical Sciences, 55A, M221–M231. 2.Guralnik, J. M., Ferrucci, L., Simonsick, E. M., Salive, M. E., & Wallace, R. B. (1995). Lower-extremity function in persons over the age of 70 years as a predictor of subsequent disability. The New England Journal of Medicine, 332, 556–561. 3. Guralnik, J. M., Simonsick, E. M., Ferrucci, L., Glynn, R. J., Berkman, L. F., Blazer, D. G., et al. (1994). A short physical performance battery assessing lower extremity function: Association with self-reported disability and prediction of mortality and nursing home admission. Journal of Gerontology: Medical Sciences, 49, M85–M94.

Description:
A new sleep screening questionnaire used in the Nord Trøndelag Health Study, including questions about snoring and sleep apnea, isomnia, sleepiness, restless legs, morning headache and night sweating during the last three months. Six of nine items are modified from a Norwegian version of the Karolinska Sleep questionnaire (KSQ, snoring/apnea/insomnia/sleepiness).
There are used only three response options in the baseline questionnaire 2 in HUNT3, but increased to five response options in the follow-up questionnaires.
The new sHUNT-Q is validatet by Engstrøm et.al. 2011.

Description: These questions are earlier used in a four item «Social Cohesion and Support Index» (SCS) which measure the individual experience of social support (Sørensen T, et al. Contribution of local community intergration and personal social network support to mental health. Norsk Epidemiologi 2002; 12 (13): 269-274). This index i based on Cobb's definition of social support (Cobb S. Social support as a moderator of life stress. Psychosom Med 1976; 35: 300-314). He describes three classes of information: One item relates to «class 1», «information leading the subject to believe that he is cared and loved» ("to have somebody close that are warm, attentive and interested in ones doings"), a second item about «class 2», «information leading the subject to believe that he is esteemed and valued» ("appreciated by friends"), and two items regarding «class 3» «information leading the subject to believe that he belongs to a network of communication and mutual obligation», one about "group belonging" and a second about "the expectation of help from the network; i.e., help when sick". In addition to its construct validity the index has shown high predictive validity, interacting with negative life events and childhood adversities with regard to mental health (Sørensen T. Mental helse i Nordkyst. Bodø: Nordland fylkeskommune, fylkeshelsesjefen, 1987., Sandanger I et al. Barndomsbelatninger, nåtidige belastninger og sosial støtte. Innvirkning på psykisk helse. I: Dalgard OS, Døhlie E, Ystgaard M, red. Sosialt nettverk, helse og samfunn. Oslo: Norwegian University Press, 1995).

Description:
The SCL-5 is a short version of the SCL 25. Based on a subsample drawn from the HUNT1 survey (n=6000), the short version of SCL 25 was examined by Tambs & Moum (1993).

Symptoms of anxiety and depression were measured by using the SCL-5 (Symptom Check-List), a five-item scale based on SCL-25, which has been proven reliable in previous studies. The SCL-5 does not differentiate well between anxiety and depression. The correlation between the SCL-5 and SCL-25 global scores and the alpha reliability for the short version are described in Tambs & Moum (1993).

Description:
SCL-10 is a short version of the Symptoms Checklist-25. The SCL-25 is a short version of the Symptom Checklist 90 (SCL-90-r, copyright by L.R. Derogatis). A version of SCL-90 is translated to Norwegian by Nielsen & Vassend.

SCL-10 consists of ten items from SCL-25 and is deigned to tap anxiety and depression. The ten items used in The Nord-Trøndelag Hearing Loss study were selected on basis of a regression analysis of a study using items from SCL-25 (Tambs & Moum 1993).

Reliability of the SCL-instruments in a Norwegian population are tested in a random sample of 10 000 participants from Statistics Norway’s (SSB) Survey of Level of Living 1998 (Strand et.al 2003).

Description:
The Finnish Diabetes Risk Score (FINDIRSC) is an eight-item scale used to predict the probability of developing type 2 diabetes within 10 years. The questionnaire was developed by Lindström and Tuomilehto (2003).



The test is designed by Professor Jaakko Tuomilehto, Department of Public Health, University of Helsinki, and Jaana Lindström, MFS, National Public Health Institute.
The questionnaire includes 8 questions with points to assess diabetes risk;
Lower than 7 points; Low risk: estimated 1 in 100 will develop disease
7–11 points; Slightly elevated risk: estimated 1 in 25 will develop disease
12–14 points; Moderate risk: estimated 1 in 6 will develop disease
15–20 points; High risk: estimated 1 in 3 will develop disease
Higher than 20 points (max 26); Very high risk: estimated 1 in 2 will develop disease.

The question text may have been slightly changed when included in the baseline questionnaire at HUNT3. However the wording/meaning is the same.

Description:
Six items are included in the HUNT1 and HUNT2 surveys designed to tap overall subjective/psychological/emotional well-being. The subjective well-being scale includes questions regarding subjective health and life satisfaction, vigor and cheerfulness, and use of tranquilizers. The items were selected from questionnaires used in previous Norwegian studies (Moum 1983; Sørensen 1987) and have been shown valid in analyses of data from the HUNT1 survey (Moum et.al 1990a, b). Issues of psychometric qualities, reliability and validity for the six-item measure of SWB are addressed in Moum, Næss, Sørensen, Tambs and Holmen (1990a) and Moum (1988). A three item version of the subjective well-being scale is also used in a prospective study of a group of adolescents based on data from the Young-HUNT1 and Young-HUNT2 surveys (Størksen et.al 2005).

A thorough literature review on subjective well-being considering the three areas measurement, causal factors and theory are presented in Diener (2009).

Description:
High resolution inductively coupled plasma– mass spectrometry (ICP-MS)

Manufacturer: Thermo Scientific TM, Germany.

The sample introduction system consisted of an SC2-DX auto-sampler with ULPA filter, a prepFAST system, concentric PFA-ST nebulizer combined with a quartz micro cyclonic Scott spray chamber with auxiliary gas port, aluminium sample and skimmer cones, and O-ring-free quartz torch and 2.5 mm injector (Elemental Scientific, Omaha, NE, USA).

The radio frequency power was set to 1350 W; nebulizer and T-connection sample gas flow were 0.75 L/min, and 0.55 L/min, respectively. Cooling gas flow was 15.5 L/min; auxiliary gas flow was 1.1 mL/min and additional gas consisted of 10% methane in argon with flow rate of 0.01 L/min. 7Li, 115In and 238U are used to tune (optimize) the instrument.

Elements were determined in three different resolutions, low (LR 400), medium (MR 5 000) and high (HR 10 000) (details in appendix B). The limit of detection (LOD) was defined as three times standard deviation (SD) of the blanks. Measurements below the detection limit were assigned with the respective LOD-value for the measurement in the dataset in the HUNT databank.The elements proved to be present as contaminants in the blood collection tubes were excluded from the analysis.

Description:
The WAIS-III was published by The Psychological Corporation in 1997. Compared to the older WAIS/WAIS-R, the WAIS-III covers a wider age range (16-89 years), is based on a larger standardization sample (2450 people) and was conformed with the third version of the Wechsler memory scale (WMS-III) . The Technical Manual (Psychological Corporation 1997/2002) describes in detail how the norm groups are recruited, how many participants there are in every age, their education level, place of residence, gender, etc. After careful selection the sample was perceived to be representative of the cognitively healthy part of the U.S. population in 1995.

The WAIS-III was published in Norway in 2003 (Psykologiforlaget, 2003). The Norwegian version is an adaptation of the Swedish translation and was based largely on lessons learned from this work, since it was assumed that the socio-economic and educational differences between the two countries were insignificant. The verbal subtest was translated into Norwegian and it was conducted a limited pilot study of reliability and factor structure. The non-verbal subtest was kept unchanged.

Description:
The WMS-III was published in Norwegian in 2008 (Pearson, 2008) as part of a Norwegian-Swedish project. The verbal subtest was translated into Norwegian and Swedish, and was tested on a Norwegian-Swedish sample consisting of 180 people. Participants were recruited with nearly the same exclusion criteria as in the United States and consisted of 93 women and 87 men. The proportion of high, medium and low education were similar at all ages, which means that the proportion of highly educated are higher than in the population as a whole and that this particularly manifests itself in the oldest ages.

The Norwegian manual describes recruitment, and the samples distribution of gender, age and education level, and the statistical analyzes done. The analyzes were considered to confirm the discoveries made with the U.S. standardization sample and although performance level of the Norwegian-Swedish cohort was slightly higher than the U.S. sample, it was decided that it was justifiable to use U.S. norms.

Description:
The ASEBA (Achenbach System of Empirically Based Assessment) is an integrated set of forms for assessing competencies, adaptive functioning, and mental health problems. The parent report, CBCL, includes 113 problem items (rated 0-1-2) constituting 8 syndrome scores, 3 composite scores (Internalizing, Externalizing and Total problems) and 6 DSM related scales. In addition, 4 competence scales are calculated based on items rating activites, social participation, academic performance (and a Total competence scale). Ratings are based on the last 6 months. Form version: 2001. Dataversion: 2001.

Description:
The classification of periodontal status included permanent teeth (3rd molars excluded). Root remnants were excluded. Implants were registered as present but were not included in the periodontal classification. Primary teeth were evaluated and included as present teeth. Missing teeth were annotated “missing due to periodontitis” if this was considered a highly probable cause.

Gingivitis
Gingivitis was calculated from bleeding on probing (BOP) and suppuration, measured at six surfaces for every tooth. “General gingivitis” was assigned if more than 30% of the surfaces showed BOP or suppuration. “Localized gingivitis” was assigned if 10-30% of the surfaces showed BOP or suppuration. Whenever less than 10% of the surfaces bled on probing or exhibited suppuration, “no gingivitis” was annotated (Trombelli et al. 2018).

Periodontal status
Classification of periodontal status was based on a classification scheme for periodontal and peri-implant diseases and conditions. This scheme was consented at the 2017 World Workshop on the Classification of Periodontal and Peri-implant Diseases and Conditions, and provided a set of criteria and case definitions of periodontal disease (Caton et al. 2018, Tonetti et al. 2018, Papapanou et al. 2018).

Additionally, a British interpretation of the classification system was applied to assign stage and grade. This was evaluated from radiographic bone loss and age, only. No modifying or complexity factors were taken into consideration (Dietrich et al. 2019).

Description:
Clinical measures of dental status were performed following standard examination protocol. The oral examination were conducted by experienced dentists and dental hygienists (n=19). Radiographs were not applied but were annotated after the clinical examination.

Tooth numbering system, ISO 3950:2016.

Instruments used for clinical examination of dental status:
- Dental Mirror (no magnification)
- Blunted probe (WHO periodontal probe, Plandent LM 550BSI)
- Air (air-water syringe on the mobile unit)
- Dental cotton rolls

Measures of dental status included registration of primary and permanent teeth, missing teeth, root remains, dental restoration, and caries. Crown caries were recorded using a 5-grade scale (Amarante et al., 1998). Caries lesions on the root surface were registered applying International Caries Detection and Assessment System (ICADS) criteria (Tropping and Pitts, 2009)

Description:
Registration of periodontal clinical parameters was performed following standard examination protocol. The oral health examinations at HUNT4 field stations were conducted by dentists or dental hygienists (n=19) from the public dental service in the northern part of Trøndelag (Den offentlige tannhelsetjenesten, Trøndelag fylkeskommune). Dental bitewing and panoramic (orthopantomogram, OPG) radiographs were obtained, but not annotated until after the data collection in HUNT4 was finalized.

Tooth numbering system, ISO 3950:2016

Instruments used for measures of periodontal parameters:
- Dental mirror (no magnification)
- WHO periodontal probe (Plandent LM 550BSI)
- Air (air-water syringe on the mobile unit)
- Dental cotton rolls

Measures of periodontal parameters included:
- Tooth mobility grade 2 or 3 (Miller 1950, Nyman et al. 1975)
- Pocket probing depth, PPD, by WHO index on six sites (db, b, mb, ml, l, dl) for every tooth (Ainamo and Bay 1976)
- PPD = 0: 0-3.5 mm
- PPD = 1: >3.5-5.5 mm
- PPD = 2: >5.5-8.5 mm
- PPD = 3: >8.5-11.5 mm
- PPD = 4: >11.5 mm
- Bleeding on probing, BOP, (yes/no) for the same six sites as PPD
- Suppuration (yes/no) for the same six sites as PPD

Description:
This scale is from Näswall et al. (2010) who adapted it from van der Vliet and Hellgren (2002) with the purpose of measuring the extent of how the work tasks demand learning of new knowledge, and that the nature of work requires continuous training. The response alternatives ranged from 1 (disagree) to 5 (agree).
(R)=reversed item

KIWEST 1.0:
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
• I am expected to constantly develop my competence
• The nature of my work means I continually have to develop myself and learn to think in new ways
• I feel pressure to continually learn new things in order to manage my work task

KIWEST 2.0:
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
There have been done some adaptations/improvements to clarify the focus:
• I am expected to continually develop my competence (“continually” replace “constantly)
• The nature of my work means I continually have to develop and think in new ways (“myself” and “learn to” are removed)
• I feel pressure to continually learn new things in order to manage my work task (R)

Description:
A continuous performance task variant. Participants were presented with a white box on the screen and asked to click or tap inside the box as quickly as possible each time the box blinked blue (GO-trials) and refrain from responding when other colors (red, yellow, green) appeared. There were 40 trials in total (80% Go-trials) and three ISIs (1000 ms / 2000 ms / 4000 ms).

Measures for each stimulus are reaction time (RT), ISI, and whether the response was a valid response (correct response for any category of response/Correct Go response or absent NoGo response), an omission (missing response to a Go trial) or commission (response to a NoGo trial). It is recommended to exclude all trials with RT lower than 100ms as these are not considered legitimate. RT in the higher end should also be considered for exclusion as they may represent laps of attention, interruptions, technical issues etc. It is advised to exclude all the participants who have clicked more (perseveration) than double the number of trials as this indicate a strategy aimed at speed not accuracy or fatigue/boredom.

225 Complex Reaction Time A continuous performance task variant. Participants were presented with a white box on the screen and asked to click or tap inside the box as quickly as possible each time the box blinked blue (GO-trials) and refrain from responding when other colors (red yellow green) appeared. There were 40 trials in total (80% Go-trials) and three ISIs (1000 ms / 2000 ms / 4000 ms).

Measures for each stimulus are reaction time (RT) ISI and whether the response was a valid response (correct response for any category of response/Correct Go response or absent NoGo response) an omission (missing response to a Go trial) or commission (response to a NoGo trial). It is recommended to exclude all trials with RT lower than 100ms as these are not considered legitimate. RT in the higher end should also be considered for exclusion as they may represent laps of attention interruptions technical issues etc. It is advised to exclude all the participants who have clicked more (perseveration) than double the number of trials as this indicate a strategy aimed at speed not accuracy or fatigue/boredom. hunt://hunt?release=hunt-db.medisin.ntnu.no&instrument=Crt hunt://hunt?release=hunt-db.medisin.ntnu.no&instrument=Crt hunt-db.medisin.ntnu.no/hunt-db/graphql/aW5zdHJ1bWVudDpDcnQ=

Instrument Title: Cornell Scale for Depression in Dementia
Description: The CSDD assesses depression in dementia. It is also valid for use in persons without dementia. The scoring is based on an interview with the caregiver most familiar with the patient, and can be supplemented with an interview/observation of the patient. The scale consists of 19 items which may have a score from 0 to 2. The total score ranges from 0 to 38. A higher score indicates more severe depression. (Alexopoulos et al., 1988)

Description:
Näswall et al. (2010) have combined items from Rizzo, House, and Lirtzman (1970) and Caplan (1971) into this scale. High score indicates that the respondent has a clear picture of the purpose of his or her own work. The four items measures to which purpose of one`s work tasks is clear. In Näswall et al. (R)=reversed item

The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).

• Explanation is clear of what has to be done
• I know what my responsibilities are
• There exist no clear, planned goals and objectives for my job (R)

KIWEST 2.0:
Item nr 3 is removed after analyses. The language is adapted to the Norwegian and Swedish versions.
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
• What is expected of me at work is clearly expressed
• I have a clear understanding of which tasks constitute my job.
• I feel that the objectives of my job are diffuse and unclear (R)

Description:
The GRIP Instrument is a web-based method for screening of pain. It was first implemented in the Tromsø Study (2015-2016) and includes the following components:

Hierarchical Body Map: Consists of 10 first-level body areas and a second level with multiple pain locations (167 for men, 168 for women). This provides information on pain location and distribution.
Follow-up Questions: For each area, questions include pain characteristics such as onset time, episode frequency and duration (including constant pain), intensity, bothersomeness, pain depth, and effects on sleep and daily activities.

Description:
The ISI is used to assess the nature, severity, and impact of sleep difficulties. It consists of seven items that evaluate sleep problems during the past two weeks, and the items are rated on a 5-point Likert scale (e.g. 0=none, 4=very severe). The items form a total score, and can be categorized by severity: absence of insomnia (0-7), sub-threshold insomnia (8-14), moderate insomnia (15-21), and severe insomnia (22-28).

Developed by Dr. Charles Morin, Université Laval and Centre de recherche Université Laval-Robert Giffard Quebec, Canada. The ISI can be used free of charge and without any written permission A Norwegian version is available, translated by Dr. Ståle Pallesen. longDesc:
253 Isomnia Severity Index The ISI is used to assess the nature severity and impact of sleep difficulties. It consists of seven items that evaluate sleep problems during the past two weeks and the items are rated on a 5-point Likert scale (e.g. 0=none 4=very severe). The items form a total score and can be categorized by severity: absence of insomnia (0-7) sub-threshold insomnia (8-14) moderate insomnia (15-21) and severe insomnia (22-28).

Description:
Näswall et al. (2010) used this scale which is adapted by Sverke & Sjøberg (1994), based on Hackman & Oldham (1975) and Walsh, Taber, & Beehr (1980) and measures the extent of autonomy and influence over how the work is carried out.

KIWEST 1.0:
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
• I have satisfactory influence over decisions concerning my job
• I can make my own decisions on how to organize my work
• There is scope for me to take own initiatives in my work
• I have a job where I can really prove my ability

KIWEST 2.0:
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
We have adapted the language to the Norwegian and Swedish versions:
• I have a sufficient degree of influence in my work
• I can make my own decisions on how to organize my work
• There is room for me to take my own initiatives at work
• I manage my work situation in the direction I want.

Description:
A pattern separation task in which participants view 175 consecutive presented images of everyday objects and decide if the image is novel, identical to a previously presented image, or similar (not identical) to a previously presented image. There were 35 “identical” trial pairs, 35 “similar” (lure) trial pairs, and 35 single presentation (foil) trials.
Measures are; Behavioral pattern separation (BPS) score (the difference between the rate of “Similar” responses given to the lure items minus “Similar” responses given to the foils (to correct for response biases), total number of correct responses to all trials (i.e., new, identical and similar), and total number of errors across all trials (i.e., new, identical and similar).

Measures are; Behavioral pattern separation (BPS) score (the difference between the rate of “Similar” responses given to the lure items minus “Similar” responses given to the foils (to correct for response biases) total number of correct responses to all trials (i.e. new identical and similar) and total number of errors across all trials (i.e. new identical and similar). hunt://hunt?release=hunt-db.medisin.ntnu.no&instrument=Mst hunt://hunt?release=hunt-db.medisin.ntnu.no&instrument=Mst hunt-db.medisin.ntnu.no/hunt-db/graphql/aW5zdHJ1bWVudDpNc3Q=

Description:
KIWEST 1,0:
“Mutual trust between employees” from COPSOQ II (Pejtersen et al., 2010) is used in this version.
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (To a very small extent) – 5 (To a very large extent)
(R)=reversed item

• Do the employees withhold information from each other? (R)
• Do the employees withhold information from the management? (R)
• Do the employees in general trust each other?

KIWEST 2,0:
“Mutual trust between employees” is removed from the 2,0 version. Instead ”Trust” from Näswall et al. (2006) is included. The scale is based on Robinson (1996) and reflects perceptions of the employer’s trustworthiness. Originally the response range is from 1 (disagree) to 5 (agree). In KIWEST 2,0 the response range from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree). The items are also slightly modified to synchronize the terms in the questionnaire. The same scale is used to examine the unit management and the management of the administrative level above:
• I can expect my unit management to treat me in a consistent and predictable way
• My unit management is always reliable
• My unit management is open and honest with me
• I am confident that I can trust my unit management
• I have complete confidence in my unit management

• I can expect the management of the next administrative level to treat me in a consistent and predictable way (”fashion” is replaced with ”way”)
• The management of the next administrative level is always reliable
• The management of the next administrative level is open and honest with me
• I am confident that I can trust the management of the next administrative level (”trust” is replaced with ”confident”)
• I have complete confidence in the management of the next administrative level

Description:
Näswall et al. (2010) has developed this scale to measure to what extent work issues are on the respondent`s mind outside work. The scale intend to capture if a perception of work spreading into other areas of life, not in terms of actual time spent on work tasks, but time thinking about work (Näswall et al., 2010). Originally the response alternatives ranged from 1 (disagree) to 5 (agree). In the 1,0 version we used the response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
(R)= reversed item

• It often occurs that I wake up in the morning and think about work related problems
• When I come home, it is easy for me to switch off from work (R)
• Those who are close to me say that I give too much of myself to my work
• I can rarely let go of thoughts concerning my work
• Even in the evenings when I am free I think about work
• My work is on my mind even in the weekends

This scale is removed from the 2,0 version. In the scale the employees experienced to meet a norm that told that they should not think about work in their leisure time. For most people at knowledge intensive workplaces this is not what they want. To think about work related issues are seen as a way of engagement and something one should not stop to do. To capture better what we think can lead to a problem we instead included DUWAS to measure workaholism.

Description:
13-item questionnaire assessing pain catastrophizing. The PCS is scored on a 5-point likert scale (0= not at all, 4= all the time). All items add up to a total score, were a score of 30 or more represents clinically relevant level of catastrophizing. In addition, PCS includes three subscales measuring rumination (items 8, 9, 10, 11), helplessness (items 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 12) and magnification (items 6, 7, 13).
Copyright 1995, 2001, 2004, 2006, 2009 Michael JL Sullivan, PhD, Departments of Psychology, Medicine, and Neurology School of Physical and Occupational Therapy McGill University. The PCS can be used free of charge and without any written permission.

Translated to Norwegian by Fernandes and colleagues, and validated in a Norwegian sample of low back pain patients (Fernandes, Storheim, Lochting, & Grotle, 2012). Permission to use the Norwegian version in this study is given by Fernandes and Storheim.

Description:
Kuvaas and Dysvik (2009) adapted this scale from Lee and Bruvold (2003). They wanted to assess employees perception of the organisation`s long-term and continuous commitment to investment in employee development. The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree),

• My organization invests heavily in employee development (e.g., by way of training, programmes and career development)
• My organization stands out as an organization that is very focused on continuous development of the skills and abilities of its employees
• By way of practices such as developmental performance appraisal, counselling systems, competence development programmes and leadership development programmes, my organization clearly demonstrates that it values development of the skills and abilities of its employees
• My organisation clearly demonstrates that it values development of the skills and abilities of its employees
• By investing time and money in employee development, my organization demonstrates that it actually invests in its employees
• I am confident that my organization will provide for the necessary training and development to solve any new tasks I may be given in the future
• I definitely think that my organization invests more heavily in employee development than comparable organizations
• My organization is effective in meeting employees' requests for internal job transfers

This scale did not at all work in the practical situations: The scale is investigating an important issue, but has not the right focus for our purpose. In our institutions it is more the employees themselves and the unit than the institution who have the responsibility for employee development. Description: The QUALID assesses quality of life (well-being) in severe dementia. The assessment is based on an interview with the caregiver who is most familiar with the patient. Instrument Title: Radiographic measures of periodontal bone loss
Description:
Dental bitewing and panoramic (OPG) radiographs were part of the oral health examination at HUNT4 field stations and are available for research projects on request.

Tooth numbering system, ISO 3950:2016

The OPG radiographs were taken using the panoramic imaging unit, Planmeca ProOne. Technical specifications: https://www.planmeca.com/imaging/panoramic-imaging/planmeca-proone/technical-specifications/. The BW radiographs were taken using an intraoral imaging unit, Planmeca Intra, with a rectangular collimator (length 35 cm) and an intraoral sensor, ProSensor HD. Edentulous participants and pregnant women (first trimester) were excluded from the BW examination.

The OPG and BW radiographs were further annotated concerning periodontal bone loss. The annotation was carried out by experienced periodontists (n=3) at the Institute of Clinical Dentistry, University of Oslo, after the data collection in HUNT4. Registrations were performed in a room with low ambient light on a computer screen (2560 x 1440 pixel resolution) applying Planmeca Romexis image software (version 4.6.0.R).

Periodontal bone loss by the means of radiographic bone level was assessed from measurements on the OPGs. The distance from the cementum enamel junction, CEJ, to the top of the bone crest and the distance from the CEJ to the root apex was measured in mm, to calculate % bone loss. The most severe bone loss was registered for each tooth. BWs were used for guidance and verification of the OPG evaluation. For a limited number of participants, BWs were the only radiographs available. For these participants, % bone loss of depicted teeth was calculated using an average root length (Fredriksen 1972). In cases of uncertainty, the level of least bone loss was chosen.
