Description:
The scale is developed for COPSOQ I (Kristensen et al., 2005) and it is also used in COPSOQ II (Pejtersen et al., 2010).

KIWEST 1.0:
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (To a very small extent) to 5 (To a very large extent).
• Do you do things at work, which are accepted by some people but not by others?
• Are contradictory demands imposed on you at work?
• Do you sometimes have to do things which ought to have been done in a different way?
• Do you sometimes have to do things which seem to be unnecessary?

KIWEST 2.0:
The scale from COPSOQ is replaced with the role conflict scale from QPS (Dallner et al., 2000). This has been done to capture the role conflict issue and the challenges in the sector better. The items are adapted to the same response alternatives as used in most of the other scales.
The response alternatives range from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
• I have to do things that I feel should have be done differently (a little bit tuned wording)
• I am often given assignments without adequate resources to complete them (To adapt the Norwegian version “often” is included)
• I frequently receive incompatible requests from two or more people (To adapt the Norwegian version “frequently” is included)
• My job involves tasks that are in conflict with my personal values

Description:
Näswall et al. (2010) has adapted the scale from Beehr, Walsh, and Taber (1976) to measure the feeling of having too much to do in too little time. Originally the response alternatives ranged from 1 (disagree) to 5 (agree).
(R)= reversed item

KIWEST 1.0:
In KIWEST The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).

• It fairly often happens that I have to work under heavy time pressure
• I often have too much to do in my job

Description:
Participants were presented with a white box on the screen and asked to click or tap inside the box as quickly as possible each time the box turned blue. There were 30 trials in total. Inter-stimulus intervals (ISI) of 2000 ms or 4000 ms were evenly divided between the trials and presented at random to reduce anticipatory responses.

Simple reaction time (SRT) in ms is given for each trial. It is recommended to exclude all trials with SRT lower than 100ms as these are not considered valid. SRT in the higher end should also be considered for exclusion as they may represent laps of attention, interruptions, technical issues

Description:
The scale is from the Nordic Questionnaire on Positive Organisational Psychology (N-POP) (Christensen et al., 2012). In N-POP cooperation was measured by three items based on the measurement of cohesion in work teams from Carless and DePaola (2000) and three items measuring “social community at wotk” from COPSOQ I and II (Pejtersen et al, 2010) collapsed into a single scale.”

KIWEST 1,0:
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
• Our team is united in trying to reach its goals for performance
• I’m happy with my team’s level of commitment to the task
• This team does give me enough opportunities to improve my personal performance
• Is there a good atmosphere between you and your colleagues?
• Is there good cooperation between the colleagues at work?
• Do you feel part of a community at your place of work?

KIWEST 2,0:
The items are synchronized to the terms in the questionnaire; some of the sentences are slightly modified. The scale from N-POP is divided into the two original scales:
Cohesion in work teams:
• At our unit we stand together in trying to reach our performance goals
• I’m happy with my unit’s level of task commitment
• This unit gives me ample opportunities to improve my personal performance
Social community:
• There is a good atmosphere between me and my colleagues
• There is a good sense of fellowship between the colleagues at my unit
• I feel that I am a part of a community at my unit

Instrument Title: Structured Clinical Interview for the DSM-IV Axis I disorders
Description:
All participants were interviewed by a psychologist using the The Structured Clinical Interview for the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders-IV (DSM-IV) Axis I disorders (First, Spitzer, Gibbon, & Williams, 1995). SCID-I is a semi-structured interview and consist of nine diagnostic modules based on DSM-IV Axis I disorders. The SCID-I/P (Patient edition) was used in this study and modified according to our study population. The SCID-I has shown good inter-rater reliability (Lobbestael, Leurgans, & Arntz, 2011). The SCID-I copyright is held by American Psychiatric Press (APA). It was translated to Norwegian in 1996 by E. Vogel, J. Monsen, P. Vogel, I. Kardel and S. Torgersen, Department of Psychology, University of Oslo. It is translated for use in research only. All of the psychologists involved were trained in the interview technique by an experienced Professor of Psychology (Tore Stiles). The interviews were also audiotaped for an inter-rater reliability test.

Comment: In addition to the variables presented in the data material, acute stress reaction, Anorexia nervosa, Bulimia nervosa, hypochondriasis, Manic episodes, Substance abuse and dependence, prescription medicine abuse and dependence were screened for specifically, but no one fulfilled criteria for these latter diagnoses.

• I know when a task is completed
• It is up to me to assess when I have completed a work assignment

Instrument Title: The Amsterdam Complex Pelvic Pain Symptom Scale
Description:
The Amsterdam Complex Pelvic Pain Symptom Scale (ACPPS) is designed to assess complex pelvic pain symptoms. It was developed to measure symptoms related to high pelvic floor muscle tone, including urinary, anorectal, and sexual dysfunction, genital/pelvic pain, and psychological distress. The ACPPS includes the following components:

Self-Report Questionnaire: A 30-item condition-specific questionnaire that covers a broad range of symptoms associated with complex pelvic pain. In addition, it has been developed a Norwegian version of the questionnaire with 16 items.
Translation and Validation: The Dutch version was translated into Norwegian, and its psychometric properties were assessed to ensure validity and reliability.

Description:
In KIWEST 1,0 The Oldenburg Burnout Inventory (OLBI )
(Demerouti et al. 2003) was used to investigate engagement. This instrument has originally been developed to assess burnout. The instrument includes both positively and negatively phrased items, and can be used to assess work engagement if recoding the negatively (Demerouti & Bakker, 2008). The OLBI includes two dimensions: one ranging from exhaustion to vigour and a second ranging from cynicism to dedication (Bakker & Demerouti, 2008). In line with Innstrand, Langballe, Falkum, and Aasland (2011) the item “I always find new and interesting aspects in my work” is changed to “I am less interested in my job now than in the beginning”. In KIWEST 1,0 the response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).
(R)= reversed item

Vigor - Exhaution:
• During my work, I often feel emotionally drained (R)
• There are days when I feel tired before I arrive at work (R)
• After work I usually feel worn out and weary (R)
• I usually feel energized at work
• After work I have enough energy for my leisure activities
• Usually, I can manage the amount of my work well
• After work, I tend to need more time than in the past in order to relax and feel better (R)
• I can tolerate the pressure of my work very well
Dedication - Disengagement:
• I am less interested in my job now than in the beginning (R)
• It happens more and more often that I talk about my work in a negative way (R)
• Lately, I tend to think less at work and do my job almost mechanically (R)
• I find my work to be a positive challenge
• Over time, one can become disconnected from this type of work (R)
• Sometimes I feel sickened by my work tasks (R)
• This is the only type of work that I can imagine myself doing.
• I feel more and more engaged in my work.

This scale is removed from the 2,0 version. Instead UWES (Schaufeli & Bakker, 2003) and DUWAS (Schaufeli, Shimazu, & Taris, 2009) are included. One reason for this is that the scale not worked well in practical survey feedback situations. This together with a wish to measure workaholism (instead of over commitment) and the third aspect of engagement “absorption” brought the replace happen.

Description: Trigger points were examined for each participant on a limited number of muscles by a single examiner. Measurement was done using the index finger to palpate muscle texture, tone and sensitivity. Participants were asked if palpation produced a pressure feeling, tenderness or pain. If pain was produced, was there any radiation and if so, to where. The examiner noted if the muscles were relaxed, felt tense, if there was a palpable trigger point and if palpation produced a “jump sign”. These observations were recorded. Trigger point assessment was done for splenius cervicis/longus colli, upper trapezius, supraspinatus, infraspinatus, levator scapulae, iliocostalis at approximately Th 12, quadratus lumborum, gluteus medius/minimus and tensor fasciae latae. Testing was done bilaterally (Simons, Travell, & Simons, 1999).

Description:
Utrecht Work Engagement Scale: Schaufeli and his co-workers have defined work engagement as a relatively positive emotional state characterized by vigour, dedication and ability to be absorbed in one’s work. Vigour is described as having much energy, having the will to make an effort at work and managing to show stamina when encountering difficulties. Dedication is described as strong involvement and identification in relation to the job, with a sense of inspiration, pride and a feeling that what one does is important. The final dimension, absorption in the job, is characterized by the ability to concentrate deeply and being so absorbed in one's tasks that time flies and it is difficult to detach oneself from the job (Schaufeli & Bakker, 2003, Schaufeli, Salanova, González-romá, & Bakker, 2002, Schaufeli & Bakker, 2004). The scale consists of nine statements, and is the most widely used instrument for measuring work engagement in questionnaires. It has been validated in many countries, including Norway, (see www.schaufeli.com for more information).

KIWEST 2.0:
Response alternatives from 0(Never), 1(A few times a year or less), 2 (Once a month or less), 3 (A few times a month), 4 (Once a week), 5 (A few times a week), 6 (Every day).
• At my work, I feel bursting with energy
• At my job, I feel strong and vigorous
• When I get up in the morning, I feel like going to work
• I am enthusiastic about my job
• My job inspires me

• I am proud on the work that I do
• I feel happy when I am working intensely
• I am immersed in my work
• I get carried away when I'm working

Description:
A variant of a list learning lest such as California verbal learning test.

A target list of 18-words from four categories was presented in three learning and recall trials. A distraction recall trial of a novel 18-word list (two overlapping categories and two new categories) followed before an immediate free recall trial. A delayed free recall trial was administered after completing other non-verbal tasks for ~15 minutes. Finally, there was a Yes/No recognition trial containing all 18 target list words, 9 distraction list words and 9 novel words.

The word lists were randomly generated for each participant from a bank of 101 words in 6 categories. A 7th category was used for the novel words in the recognition trial.

Description:
An object-location memory task. 10 tiles with color drawings of real-life objects were randomly placed within a blank square on the screen. The tiles were visible for 60 seconds (learning period) before they were moved below the blank square and the participant asked to place them back from memory (immediate recall). After a delay of ~20 minutes the user completed a delayed recall trial. Finally, there was a Yes/No recognition trial containing the 10 target objects and 8 novel objects.

Participants had 60 seconds to memorize the location of 10 colored drawings placed within a white box. After the encoding period, all objects were moved outside the box and participants had to drag and drop each object into its original location (i.e. immediate recall). After approximately 20 minutes completing other tests (median time between finishing immediate recall and starting delayed recall was 22.19 minutes), participants were asked to drag and drop each object into its original location again in the delayed recall. Total score is number of correctly placed objects.
longDesc:
313 Visual memory An object-location memory task. 10 tiles with color drawings of real-life objects were randomly placed within a blank square on the screen. The tiles were visible for 60 seconds (learning period) before they were moved below the blank square and the participant asked to place them back from memory (immediate recall). After a delay of ~20 minutes the user completed a delayed recall trial. Finally there was a Yes/No recognition trial containing the 10 target objects and 8 novel objects.

Participants had 60 seconds to memorize the location of 10 colored drawings placed within a white box. After the encoding period all objects were moved outside the box and participants had to drag and drop each object into its original location (i.e. immediate recall). After approximately 20 minutes completing other tests (median time between finishing immediate recall and starting delayed recall was 22.19 minutes) participants were asked to drag and drop each object into its original location again in the delayed recall. Instrument Title: West Haven-Yale Multidimensional Pain Inventory Part II
Description:
West Haven-Yale Multidimensional Pain Inventory (WHYMPI) – Part II assess patients’ perceptions of sigificant others responses to their pain. It consists of three subscales that assess the degree to which significant others display solicitous, distracting or punishing responses to their pain behaviors and complaints. The items are rated on a 7-point scale (0= never, 6=very often).

Copyright 1985: Robert D. Kerns, Dennis C. Turk, and Thomas E. Rudy. Permission to use this scale in this study is given by Dr. Kerns. WHYMPI- part II has been translated to Norwegian by Dr. Tore Stiles, Professor in Psychology, NTNU. It has not yet been validated.

Description:
Innstrand, Langballe, Falkum and Gjerløw (2009) have slightly modified the scale from Wayne, Musisca, and Fleeson (2004). Originally the respondents indicated whether the statements were in accord with their own experience based on a 5-point scale from 1 (totally disagree) to 5 (totally agree).

KIWEST 1.0:
The response alternatives ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree)..
• My job reduces the effort I can give to activities at home
• Stress at work makes me irritable at home
• My job makes me feel too tired to do the things that need attention at home
• Job worries or problems distract me when I am at home

There has not been done any changes from the 1.0 version to the 2.0 version.
